abstract: It would be a "fatal mistake" for any country to assume it will not be hit by the new coronavirus, and rich countries that might have thought they were safer should expect surprises, the head of the World Health Organization said on Thursday.
snippet: It would be a "fatal mistake" for any country to assume it will not be hit by the new coronavirus, and rich countries that might have thought they were safer should expect surprises, the head of the World Health Organization said on Thursday.
lead_paragraph: GENEVA — It would be a "fatal mistake" for any country to assume it will not be hit by the new coronavirus, and rich countries that might have thought they were safer should expect surprises, the head of the World Health Organization said on Thursday.
headline_main: 'Fatal Mistake' for Countries to Assume They Won't Get Coronavirus - WHO Chief
headline_print_headline: 'Fatal Mistake' for Countries to Assume They Won't Get Coronavirus - WHO Chief

abstract: The U.S. economy grew moderately in the fourth quarter, the government confirmed, and is facing a bumpy road in early 2020 amid the fast-spreading coronavirus that has left financial markets fearing a recession.
snippet: The U.S. economy grew moderately in the fourth quarter, the government confirmed, and is facing a bumpy road in early 2020 amid the fast-spreading coronavirus that has left financial markets fearing a recession.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The U.S. economy grew moderately in the fourth quarter, the government confirmed, and is facing a bumpy road in early 2020 amid the fast-spreading coronavirus that has left financial markets fearing a recession.
headline_main: U.S. Economy Grows Steadily in Fourth-Quarter, but Coronavirus Looms Large
headline_print_headline: U.S. Economy Grows Steadily in Fourth-Quarter, but Coronavirus Looms Large

abstract: The gunman and the five people he killed were all employees of the brewery.
snippet: The gunman and the five people he killed were all employees of the brewery.
lead_paragraph: The authorities in Milwaukee were working on Thursday to piece together how and why a 51-year-old gunman killed five of his co-workers at the city’s sprawling Molson Coors campus.

abstract: The U.S. economy grew at an annual rate of 2.1% in the final quarter of last year, but damage from the spreading coronavirus is likely depressing growth in the current quarter and for the rest of the year.

abstract: Orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket manufactured goods dipped in January, pulled down by decreased demand for cars, auto parts and military aircraft.
snippet: Orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket manufactured goods dipped in January, pulled down by decreased demand for cars, auto parts and military aircraft.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket manufactured goods dipped in January, pulled down by decreased demand for cars, auto parts and military aircraft.
headline_main: US Orders for Durable Goods Slip 0.2% in January
headline_print_headline: US Orders for Durable Goods Slip 0.2% in January

abstract: The virus, which has now spread to 47 countries, has put pressure on businesses and supply chains around the world.
snippet: The virus, which has now spread to 47 countries, has put pressure on businesses and supply chains around the world.
lead_paragraph: The global stock market slid for the sixth straight day on Thursday, as the S&P 500 index plunged to its worst loss in almost nine years and investors worldwide grew increasingly fearful that the coronavirus outbreak could cause a recession as it squeezes corporate profits.

abstract: Americans have widespread concerns about the security and integrity of elections, with few saying they have high confidence that votes in the 2020 presidential election will be counted accurately.

lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Americans have widespread concerns about the security and integrity of elections, with few saying they have high confidence that votes in the 2020 presidential election will be counted accurately.
